âœ… P3: Iris Dataset using Pandas

Sure-Shot Theory:

Pandas is used for data manipulation, cleaning, and analysis.
The Iris dataset is loaded into a DataFrame to study its structure, missing values, and statistical properties.
GroupBy operations help analyze features species-wise.
Correlation analysis is used to identify relationships between numerical attributes.




import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv("iris.csv")

# Display shape, type, head & tail
print("Shape:", df.shape)
print("Type:\n", df.dtypes)
print("First 4 rows:\n", df.head(4))
print("Last 4 rows:\n", df.tail(4))

# Replace abnormal symbols with NaN
df.replace(['??', '##'], np.nan, inplace=True)

# Count missing values
print("Missing Values:\n", df.isnull().sum())

# Basic statistics
print("Statistical Summary:\n", df.describe())

# Species-wise statistics
print("Species-wise Mean:\n", df.groupby('Species').mean())

# Replace missing values
df['PetalWidthCm'].fillna(df['PetalWidthCm'].mean(), inplace=True)
df['SepalLengthCm'].fillna(df['SepalLengthCm'].mode()[0], inplace=True)

# Max & Min values
print("Max Sepal Length:\n", df.loc[df['SepalLengthCm'].idxmax()])
print("Min Petal Width:\n", df.loc[df['PetalWidthCm'].idxmin()])

# Sort by Sepal Length
print("Sorted Data:\n", df.sort_values('SepalLengthCm'))

# Correlation
print("Correlation Matrix:\n", df.corr())



